Discussion 11

Batter up

Well be looking at data from all 30 Major League Baseball teams and examining the linear relationship between runs scored in a season and a number of other player statistics. Our aim will be to summarize these relationships both graphically and numerically in order to find which variable, if any, helps us best predict a teams runs scored in a season.

The data

Lets load up the data for the 2011 season.

load("/Users/cwong79/Dropbox/Public/CUNY/DATA 605/more/mlb11.RData")

In addition to runs scored, there are seven traditionally used variables in the data set: at-bats, hits, home runs, batting average, strikeouts, stolen bases, and wins. There are also three newer variables: on-base percentage, slugging percentage, and on-base plus slugging.

If the relationship looks linear, we can quantify the strength of the relationship with the correlation coefficient. Here I am comparing runs versus at bats.

cor(mlb11$runs, mlb11$at_bats)
## [1] 0.610627

Here is another comparison of runs versus hits.

cor(mlb11$runs, mlb11$hits)
## [1] 0.8012108
plot_ss(x = mlb11$hits, y = mlb11$runs)

The hits variable appears to predict runs better than at_bats since the r-squared value is higher and therefore the variability that can be explained by the model is higher.

runs ~ hits = 0.6419 runs ~ at_bats = 0.3729

m2 <- lm(runs ~ hits, data = mlb11)
summary(m2)

Bat_avg has the highest R^2 value at 0.6561, therefore, best predicts runs.

plot(mlb11$runs ~ mlb11$bat_avg)
m3 <- lm(runs ~ bat_avg, data = mlb11)
abline(m3)

new_obs is the best predictor of runs with an R^2 value of 0.9349. The results does make sense because being on base and hitting a ball is a definitive criteria to make a run.

plot(mlb11$runs ~ mlb11$new_obs)
m4 <- lm(runs ~ new_obs, data = mlb11)
abline(m4)

summary(m4)

  • Check the model diagnostics for the regression model with the variable you decided was the best predictor for runs.
plot(m4$residuals ~ mlb11$new_obs)
abline(h = 0, lty = 3)

There seems to be constant variability as the points do not seem to follow any patterns.

hist(m4$residuals)

The histogram of new_obs is nearly symmetrical and unimodal.

qqnorm(m4$residuals)
qqline(m4$residuals)

The plot shows a very clear linear relationship.
